<section class="issue-grid">
    <div class="issue-card">
        <h3>Region IV-A (CALABARZON)</h3>
        <p><strong>San Isidro, Gumaca • Quezon</strong></p>
        <p>Unfinished Farm-to-Market Road ,  only 30% complete since 2021.</p>
        <details>
           <summary>“We were told it would be concrete by 2023. Still waiting.”<br></summary>
            <p  style="text-align: justify;">The Farm-to-Market Road project in San Isidro, Gumaca, Quezon, part of Region IV-A (CALABARZON), has faced significant delays, with only 30% completion since its initiation in 2021. Despite community expectations and promises that the road would be fully concreted by 2023, progress has stalled, leaving residents frustrated and underserved. A local voice captured the sentiment plainly: “We were told it would be concrete by 2023. Still waiting.” This road is crucial for transporting agricultural goods efficiently, and its unfinished state hampers farmers’ access to markets, potentially increasing costs and post-harvest losses. While the Department of Agriculture has allocated billions for Farm-to-Market Roads nationwide, including CALABARZON, there’s no clear indication that San Isidro’s project is prioritized in the current rollout. The delay may stem from funding gaps, contractor issues, or logistical challenges, but without transparency from local government units or the Department of Public Works and Highways, the community remains in limbo. For civic monitors or watchdog groups, this case highlights the importance of tracking infrastructure promises and demanding accountability through public records, interviews, and Freedom of Information requests.</p>
        </details>
        <a href="https://gumaca.gov.ph/inspection-of-farm-to-market-road-project"><i>Read more...</i></a>
    </div>

    <div class="issue-card">
        <h3>Region VIII (Eastern Visayas)</h3>
        <p><strong>Anibong, Tacloban City • Leyte</strong></p>
        <details>
            <summary>Collapsed drainage system causing knee-deep flooding during moderate rains.</summary>
            <P style="text-align: justify;">The collapsed drainage system in Anibong, Tacloban City, Leyte, part of Region VIII (Eastern Visayas), has become a persistent urban hazard, triggering knee-deep flooding even during moderate rains. This low-lying coastal barangay, already vulnerable to climate-related risks, suffers from outdated or structurally compromised drainage infrastructure that fails to channel runoff effectively. Recent inspections by the Tacloban City District Engineering Office (TCDEO) confirmed the severity of the issue, prompting early-morning deployment of maintenance teams to declog road drainages. However, these stopgap measures have proven insufficient, as flooding continues to disrupt daily life, impede mobility, and raise public health concerns. The situation is exacerbated by the shear line weather phenomenon, which brings frequent rainfall to Leyte and Samar, overwhelming drainage systems not designed for such intensity. In late 2023, Eastern Visayas recorded over ₱515 million in damage to public infrastructure and agriculture due to flooding, with Tacloban among the hardest-hit areas. Road closures, landslides, and submerged communities have become recurring challenges, underscoring the need for long-term solutions. For Anibong, this means not just maintenance but full-scale rehabilitation of its drainage network, backed by transparent reporting and sustained investment from both local and national agencies. Civic monitors and watchdog groups can play a vital role by documenting these failures, filing Freedom of Information requests, and amplifying community voices to ensure infrastructure promises translate into real resilience.</P>
        </details>
        <a href="https://gumaca.gov.ph/inspection-of-farm-to-market-road-project"><i>Read more...</i></a>

    </div>

    <div class="issue-card">
        <h3>BARMM</h3>
        <p><strong>Poblacion, Buluan • Maguindanao del Sur</strong></p>
        <details>
            <summary>No access to clean water. ₱2.5M project approved but never started.</summary>
            <p style="text-align: justify;">In Poblacion, Buluan, Maguindanao del Sur, residents continue to suffer from a lack of access to clean water despite a ₱2.5 million project that was approved to address the issue but never initiated. This failure has left the community reliant on unsafe or distant water sources, raising serious health and sanitation concerns. While BARMM has made progress in installing WASH facilities in other municipalities, Poblacion remains overlooked, highlighting gaps in regional prioritization and accountability. Without transparency from local officials or follow-through on infrastructure commitments, the promise of clean water remains unmet, deepening the daily hardship of affected families</p>
        </details>
        <a href="https://gumaca.gov.ph/inspection-of-farm-to-market-road-project"><i>Read more...</i></a>
    </div>

    <div class="issue-card">
        <h3>Region II (Cagayan Valley)</h3>
        <p><strong>Minanga, Ilagan City • Isabela</strong></p>
        <details>
            <summary>Collapsed wooden bridge washed away in 2022 ,  still unrepaired.</summary>
            <P style="text-align: justify;">The bridge in Minanga, Ilagan City, part of Region II (Cagayan Valley), was a vital link for local residents, especially farmers and students, until it was destroyed by flooding in 2022. Since then, no reconstruction has taken place, forcing people to take longer, riskier routes or cross waterways using makeshift paths. The lack of repair not only disrupts daily mobility but also poses serious safety risks, especially during the rainy season when rivers swell and become impassable. While national attention recently focused on the collapse of the retrofitted Cabagan-Santa Maria Bridge in the same province, despite ₱840 million in funding, Minanga’s case highlights how smaller, rural infrastructure often goes unnoticed and unfunded. The continued neglect raises concerns about regional equity in infrastructure spending and the effectiveness of local government oversight. Without urgent intervention, Minanga’s residents remain stranded by a broken promise of connectivity.</p>
        </details>
        <a href="https://gumaca.gov.ph/inspection-of-farm-to-market-road-project"><i>Read more...</i></a>
    </div>
</section>

